54. The practice of leaving great sums of money to friends, tho' one had near relations, was common in *Greece* as well as *Rome*; as we may gather from *Lucian*. This practice prevails much less in modern times; and BEN. JOHNSON's VOLPONE is therefore almost entirely extracted from antient authors, and suits better the manners of those times.

{#84}
It may justly be thought, that the liberty of divorces in *Rome* was another discouragement to marriage. Such a practice prevents not quarrels from _humour_, but rather increases them; and occasions also those from _interest_, which are much more dangerous and destructive. See farther on this head, Essays moral, political, and literary, Part I. essay XIX. Perhaps too the unnatural lusts of the antients ought to be taken into consideration, as of some moment.

